# Multi‑agent reinforcement learning  

'''Multi‑agent reinforcement learning''' (often abbreviated **MARL**) is a sub‑field of [[reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning)] that studies how multiple autonomous agents can learn to make sequential decisions in a shared environment when their interests may align, conflict, or be completely antagonistic.  In contrast to single‑agent reinforcement learning, where the learning problem is typically static and the environment is stationary, MARL introduces a dynamic, non‑stationary system in which each agent’s policy can influence – and be influenced by – the policies of the other agents.  This interaction gives rise to phenomena such as [[group dynamics](/Group_dynamics)], [[game theory](/Game_theory)], and [[repeated games](/Repeated_game)], and it has motivated the development of a rich taxonomy of learning paradigms, problem classes, and evaluation metrics that are unique to the multi‑agent setting.  

== Overview ==  

Multi‑agent reinforcement learning sits at the intersection of several research traditions, including [[machine learning](/Machine_learning)], [[data mining](/Data_mining)], and [[artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence)].  It is positioned as a distinct sub‑field within the broader [[machine learning](/Machine_learning)] ecosystem, alongside [[supervised learning](/Supervised_learning)], [[unsupervised learning](/Unsupervised_learning)], [[semi‑supervised learning](/Semi-supervised_learning)], [[online learning](/Online_machine_learning)], [[batch learning](/Batch_learning)], [[curriculum learning](/Curriculum_learning)], [[rule‑based learning](/Rule-based_machine_learning)], [[neuro‑symbolic AI](/Neuro-symbolic_AI)], [[neuromorphic engineering](/Neuromorphic_engineering)], and [[quantum machine learning](/Quantum_machine_learning)]].  

The discipline addresses a variety of [[problems](/Problem)] that arise when agents must coordinate or compete, such as [[classification](/Statistical_classification)], [[generative modeling](/Generative_model)], [[regression](/Regression_analysis)], [[clustering](/Cluster_analysis)], [[dimensionality reduction](/Dimensionality_reduction)], [[density estimation](/Density_estimation)], [[anomaly detection](/Anomaly_detection)], [[data cleaning](/Data_cleaning)], [[AutoML](/Automated_machine_learning)], [[association rules](/Association_rule_learning)], [[semantic analysis](/Semantic_analysis_(machine_learning))], [[structured prediction](/Structured_prediction)], [[feature engineering](/Feature_engineering)], [[feature learning](/Feature_learning)], [[learning to rank](/Learning_to_rank)], [[grammar induction](/Grammar_induction)], [[ontology learning](/Ontology_learning)], and [[multimodal learning](/Multimodal_learning)].  

== Paradigms ==  

The canonical [[reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning)] paradigms that have been extended to the multi‑agent context include:  

* [[Supervised learning](/Supervised_learning)] – wherein a central supervisor provides labeled examples to each agent.  
* [[Unsupervised learning](/Unsupervised_learning)] – used when agents must discover structure in unlabeled interaction data.  
* [[Semi‑supervised learning](/Semi-supervised_learning)] – a hybrid where limited supervision is combined with large amounts of interaction data.  
* [[Self‑supervised learning](/Self-supervised_learning)] – agents generate their own training signals from the environment.  
* [[Reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning)] – the primary framework for MARL, where agents optimise long‑term reward through trial‑and‑error.  
* [[Meta‑learning](/Meta-learning_(computer_science))] – techniques that enable agents to quickly adapt to new tasks or other agents.  
* [[Online learning](/Online_machine_learning)] – methods that update policies continuously as new interaction data arrives.  
* [[Batch learning](/Batch_learning)] – training on a fixed dataset of past experiences.  
* [[Curriculum learning](/Curriculum_learning)] – presenting agents with progressively harder tasks.  
* [[Rule‑based learning](/Rule-based_machine_learning)] – incorporating hand‑crafted heuristics or rules into the learning process.  
* [[Neuro‑symbolic AI](/Neuro-symbolic_AI)] – integrating symbolic reasoning with neural perception.  
* [[Neuromorphic engineering](/Neuromorphic_engineering)] – hardware‑inspired learning that mimics brain dynamics.  
* [[Quantum machine learning](/Quantum_machine_learning)] – exploratory approaches that leverage quantum computation for multi‑agent problems.  

== Problems ==  

Research in MARL often clusters around a set of canonical problem classes, each of which can be instantiated in a multi‑agent context:  

* [[Classification](/Statistical_classification)] – assigning labels to joint states observed by multiple agents.  
* [[Generative modeling](/Generative_model)] – generating plausible joint trajectories for multiple agents.  
* [[Regression](/Regression_analysis)] – predicting future rewards or states for collections of agents.  
* [[Clustering](/Cluster_analysis)] – grouping agents with similar policy behaviours.  
* [[Dimensionality reduction](/Dimensionality_reduction)] – compressing high‑dimensional joint observations into a compact representation.  
* [[Density estimation](/Density_estimation)] – modelling the distribution of joint actions across the population.  
* [[Anomaly detection](/Anomaly_detection)] – identifying out‑of‑distribution interactions that may indicate adversarial behaviour.  
* [[Data cleaning](/Data_cleaning)] – filtering noisy or corrupted interaction logs.  
* [[AutoML](/Automated_machine_learning)] – automatically selecting architectures and hyper‑parameters for multi‑agent systems.  
* [[Association rules](/Association_rule_learning)] – mining frequent patterns in joint action histories.  
* [[Semantic analysis](/Semantic_analysis_(machine_learning))] – interpreting natural‑language communication between agents.  
* [[Structured prediction](/Structured_prediction)] – jointly predicting complex output structures such as interaction graphs.  
* [[Feature engineering](/Feature_engineering)] – designing handcrafted descriptors for multi‑agent observations.  
* [[Feature learning](/Feature_learning)] – letting agents discover useful representations through interaction.  
* [[Learning to rank](/Learning_to_rank)] – ordering joint actions according to expected collective reward.  
* [[Grammar induction](/Grammar_induction)] – discovering interaction grammars that govern communication protocols.  
* [[Ontology learning](/Ontology_learning)] – building shared vocabularies for multi‑agent interaction.  
* [[Multimodal learning](/Multimodal_learning)] – integrating vision, language, and proprioception in heterogeneous agent teams.  

== Supervised learning ==  

Within the broader supervised learning umbrella, MARL incorporates a number of specialized algorithms that have proven effective for coordinating multiple decision‑makers:  

* [[Apprenticeship learning](/Apprenticeship_learning)] – learning policies by imitation of expert demonstrations.  
* [[Decision trees](/Decision_tree_learning)] – constructing interpretable joint action policies.  
* [[Ensembles](/Ensemble_learning)] – aggregating multiple policy models to improve robustness.  
* [[Bagging](/Bootstrap_aggregating)] – reducing variance by training on bootstrap samples of interaction data.  
* [[Boosting](/Boosting_(machine_learning))] – sequentially refining policies that previously under‑performed.  
* [[Random forest](/Random_forest)] – a collection of decision trees that vote on the final joint action.  
* [[k -NN]] – a nearest‑neighbour approach to policy retrieval based on observed joint histories.  
* [[Linear regression](/Linear_regression)] – modelling linear reward functions across agents.  
* [[Naive Bayes](/Naive_Bayes_classifier)] – probabilistic classification of joint states.  
* [[Artificial neural networks](/Artificial_neural_network)] – function approximators for high‑dimensional policy spaces.  
* [[Logistic regression](/Logistic_regression)] – modelling binary outcome predictions in multi‑agent settings.  
* [[Perceptron](/Perceptron)] – a foundational linear classifier for simple coordination tasks.  
* [[Relevance vector machine (RVM)](/Relevance_vector_machine)] – a sparse Bayesian alternative to linear models.  
* [[Support vector machine (SVM)](/Support_vector_machine)] – margin‑maximising classifiers for joint state discrimination.  

== Clustering ==  

Clustering techniques are employed to discover groups of agents with similar behavioural tendencies:  

* [[BIRCH](/BIRCH)] – a hierarchical clustering algorithm suited for incremental updates.  
* [[CURE](/CURE_algorithm)] – a centroid‑based method that tolerates non‑spherical clusters.  
* [[Hierarchical](/Hierarchical_clustering)] – building a tree of cluster merges to capture multi‑scale interactions.  
* [[k -means]] – the classic partitioning algorithm applied to joint action embeddings.  
* [[Fuzzy](/Fuzzy_clustering)] – allowing agents to belong partially to multiple clusters.  
* [[Expectation%E2%80%93maximization (EM)](/Expectation%E2%80%93maximization_algorithm)] – an iterative method for estimating cluster parameters.  
* [[DBSCAN](/DBSCAN)] – density‑based clustering that identifies outliers in joint behaviour.  
* [[OPTICS](/OPTICS_algorithm)] – an extension of DBSCAN that handles varying densities.  
* [[Mean shift](/Mean_shift)] – a mode‑seeking algorithm for estimating underlying data distributions.  

== Dimensionality reduction ==  

To cope with the curse of dimensionality in joint state‑action spaces, MARL research frequently applies dimensionality‑reduction strategies:  

* [[Factor analysis](/Factor_analysis)] – modelling latent factors that generate observed joint observations.  
* [[CCA](/Canonical_correlation)] – finding linear combinations of variables that are maximally correlated across agents.  
* [[ICA](/Independent_component_analysis)] – separating independent sources of variation in multi‑agent data.  
* [[LDA](/Linear_discriminant_analysis)] – projecting data onto a discriminant space that maximises class separability.  
* [[NMF](/Non-negative_matrix_factorization)] – factorising non‑negative interaction matrices.  
* [[PCA](/Principal_component_analysis)] – a linear technique for reducing dimensionality while preserving variance.  
* [[PGD](/Proper_generalized_decomposition)] – a generalisation of PCA for non‑Gaussian data.  
* [[t‑SNE](/T-distributed_stochastic_neighbor_embedding)] – a non‑linear method for visualising high‑dimensional joint behaviours.  
* [[SDL](/Sparse_dictionary_learning)] – learning compact dictionary representations of interaction patterns.  

== Structured prediction ==  

MARL often requires joint predictions over complex structured outputs such as interaction graphs or coordination sequences:  

* [[Graphical models](/Graphical_model)] – probabilistic frameworks for representing dependencies among agents.  
* [[Bayes net](/Bayesian_network)] – directed acyclic graphs that encode conditional dependencies.  
* [[Conditional random field](/Conditional_random_field)] – discriminative models for labelling structured outputs.  
* [[Hidden Markov](/Hidden_Markov_model)] – stochastic models for sequential interaction patterns.  

== Anomaly detection ==  

Detecting unusual or potentially adversarial behaviour in multi‑agent systems involves:  

* [[RANSAC](/Random_sample_consensus)] – robust fitting that tolerates outliers in joint trajectories.  
* [[Local outlier factor](/Local_outlier_factor)] – a density‑based measure of how isolated an agent’s behaviour is.  
* [[Isolation forest](/Isolation_forest)] – an ensemble method that isolates anomalies through random partitioning.  

== Neural networks ==  

The deep learning boom has spurred a multitude of neural architectures tailored for multi‑agent contexts:  

* [[Autoencoder](/Autoencoder)] – learning compact encodings of joint observation histories.  
* [[Deep learning](/Deep_learning)] – the overarching paradigm for training large‑scale multi‑agent policies.  
* [[Feedforward neural network](/Feedforward_neural_network)] – basic fully‑connected models for static joint states.  
* [[Recurrent neural network](/Recurrent_neural_network)] – handling temporal dependencies in multi‑agent interaction.  
* [[LSTM](/Long_short-term_memory)] – gated recurrent units for long‑range memory of joint histories.  
* [[GRU](/Gated_recurrent_unit)] – a simpler variant of LSTM with fewer parameters.  
* [[ESN](/Echo_state_network)] – reservoir computing for fast adaptation to new interaction patterns.  
* [[reservoir computing](/Reservoir_computing)] – a computational framework that leverages random recurrent networks.  
* [[Boltzmann machine](/Boltzmann_machine)] – stochastic neural models for energy‑based joint policy representation.  
* [[Restricted](/Restricted_Boltzmann_machine)] – a simplified Boltzmann model used for modelling visible‑hidden interactions.  
* [[GAN](/Generative_adversarial_network)] – generating realistic joint trajectories through adversarial training.  
* [[Diffusion model](/Diffusion_model)] – a newer generative technique for synthesising multi‑agent sequences.  
* [[SOM](/Self-organizing_map)] – unsupervised clustering of agent behaviours in a topological map.  
* [[Convolutional neural network](/Convolutional_neural_network)] – exploiting spatial structure in multi‑agent perception (e.g., map‑based environments).  
* [[U‑Net](/U-Net)] – a symmetric encoder‑decoder architecture used for precise joint state segmentation.  
* [[LeNet](/LeNet)] – one of the earliest convolutional architectures, occasionally repurposed for small‑scale MARL tasks.  
* [[AlexNet](/AlexNet)] – a deep convolutional model that has been adapted for multi‑modal input in multi‑agent vision tasks.  
* [[DeepDream](/DeepDream)] – an artistic visualisation technique that has been repurposed for exploring activation patterns in multi‑agent networks.  
* [[Neural field](/Neural_field)] – continuous‑state models for representing large populations of agents.  
* [[Neural radiance field](/Neural_radiance_field)] – rendering‑oriented models that have found use in simulating multi‑agent perception of 3‑D environments.  
* [[Physics‑informed neural networks](/Physics-informed_neural_networks)] – embedding physical constraints into joint dynamics predictions.  
* [[Transformer](/Transformer_(deep_learning_architecture))] – attention‑based architectures for modelling long‑range dependencies across agents.  
* [[Vision](/Vision_transformer)] – a transformer variant specialised for visual inputs in multi‑agent perception.  
* [[Mamba](/Mamba_(deep_learning_architecture))] – a state‑space model offering efficient long‑sequence processing for multi‑agent trajectories.  
* [[Spiking neural network](/Spiking_neural_network)] – bio‑inspired models that simulate discrete spikes in multi‑agent communication.  
* [[Memtransistor](/Memtransistor)] – emerging nano‑electronic devices that can implement stochastic synaptic updates in hardware‑accelerated MARL.  
* [[Electrochemical RAM](/Electrochemical_RAM) (ECRAM)] – a memory technology that has been explored for storing learned joint policies.  

== Reinforcement learning ==  

Reinforcement learning remains the core optimisation framework for MARL, with a suite of algorithms that have been adapted or invented for multi‑agent scenarios:  

* [[Q‑learning](/Q‑learning)] – value‑based methods that estimate action‑value functions in joint spaces.  
* [[Policy gradient](/Policy_gradient_method)] – direct optimisation of stochastic policies across multiple agents.  
* [[SARSA](/State%E2%80%93action%E2%80%93reward%E2%80%93state%E2%80%93action)] – an on‑policy algorithm that updates Q‑values using the next action taken by the joint policy.  
* [[Temporal difference (TD)](/Temporal_difference_learning)] – a family of bootstrapping methods for estimating value functions in multi‑agent settings.  
* [[Multi‑agent]] – a generic descriptor for any RL formulation involving more than one decision‑maker.  
* [[Self‑play](/Self‑play_(reinforcement_learning_technique))] – a technique where agents compete or cooperate against clones of themselves, enabling the emergence of curricula and emergent strategies.  

== Learning with humans ==  

MARL research also investigates how machines can interact safely and productively with human participants:  

* [[Active learning](/Active_learning_(machine_learning))] – querying humans for informative examples in multi‑agent data collection.  
* [[Crowdsourcing](/Crowdsourcing)] – aggregating human judgments to shape joint reward signals.  
* [[Human‑in‑the‑loop](/Human-in-the-loop)] – integrating human supervisors directly into the learning loop of multi‑agent systems.  
* [[Mechanistic interpretability](/Mechanistic_interpretability)] – analysing the internal representations that drive multi‑agent decisions.  
* [[RLHF](/Reinforcement_learning_from_human_feedback)] – leveraging human feedback to shape multi‑agent reward functions and alignment.  

== Model diagnostics ==  

Assessing the performance and safety of multi‑agent policies relies on a battery of diagnostic tools:  

* [[Coefficient of determination](/Coefficient_of_determination)] – measuring how well a model explains observed joint outcomes.  
* [[Confusion matrix](/Confusion_matrix)] – summarising classification errors across joint action predictions.  
* [[Learning curve](/Learning_curve_(machine_learning))] – plotting performance over training steps to diagnose convergence issues.  
* [[ROC curve](/Receiver_operating_characteristic)] – evaluating trade‑offs between detection rates and false positives in anomaly identification.  

